history.content:
The two main topics you need to study are 1) time-domain analysis and 2) frequency-domain analysis of circuits containing R, C, L. Since you have already taken math54, it should be quite easy to pick up the time-domain analysis of RC and RLC circuits. For the frequency-domain part, you just need to make sure you understand phasors, impedance, and Bode plots. They are all small topics and shouldn't take too long to learn. 16B is almost a control class now, so there isn't too much to absorb if you want to take 105.

105 spends the first week reviewing the topics I mentioned above, but the professor does assume you know most of the stuff. Honestly, it's probably better to not have gone through 16B since it doesn't do any justice to circuit design. I felt I pretty much relearned AC circuits in 105.

I'm unfortunately unable to take 16B this coming semester, but I really want to learn more about hardware. I'm definitely down to learn the circuits part of 16B on my own if this is viable and I'm mostly wondering how much 105 goes over previous 16A/16B material before diving into new material. I should note that I've already taken 16A and 54. 

My main questions are:

1. How much background knowledge is assumed in 105 as opposed to being being taught again in the class 

2. How hard would it be to learn the background material on my own by the time the semester starts?
history.subject: EE105 without 16B?
